  "prompt": "Why is John Wick called Baba Yaga?",
  "response": "In the \"John Wick\" film series, the character John Wick is referred to as \"Baba Yaga\" as a nod to the folklore surrounding this mythical figure. In Slavic folklore, Baba Yaga is often depicted as a supernatural being or witch who is both feared and respected. She is known for her ambiguous morality and for being a formidable figure who can either help or hinder those who encounter her.\n\nThe use of \"Baba Yaga\" to describe John Wick emphasizes his fearsome reputation as an assassin and highlights his status as a legendary figure in the underworld. In the context of the films, it signifies that he is not just an ordinary hitman; he is a highly skilled and almost mythical figure, much like the folkloric Baba Yaga. Wick's prowess, relentless nature, and the respect (and fear) he instills in others parallel the qualities associated with the traditional depiction of Baba Yaga. The term serves to enhance his mystique and place him in a larger narrative of legendary assassins and skilled fighters.",
